english:
  title: Record of Paintings
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Hall of Constant Diligence loves calligraphy and painting. Whenever its master hears that someone possesses even a single-line letter or scrap of a painting, he buys it generously, selects the finest pieces, has them mounted, and treasures them in his collection. One day, he brought them all out to show me, saying: "By nature I love these things—yet this too is an affliction. After ten years of searching and gathering far and wide, I have amassed this much. Alas, all things have their time of becoming and decay, their moments of gathering and scattering. How can I know that what is complete today will not crumble tomorrow? And this gathering and scattering—who can say what will come to pass? Long ago, Han Yu wrote a record of Du Gu Sheng's paintings to preserve them for himself. Thus I too have composed a poem to record mine. Now compose a record for me."

    I have heard that Zhang Dun-jian's collection held merely a dozen scrolls, and yet Bai Juyi still wrote a record for it. How much more should a collection refined from all of antiquity and reaching several hundred scrolls not be recorded and transmitted to posterity?

    Observing this refined collection: From the Eastern Jin, we have obtained one master—Gu Kaizhi, whose courtesy name was Hu Tou. Broadly learned and gifted, he attained the sublime in painting, yet guarded his works so jealously that few in the world ever saw them. Now we have a printed copy of his Water and Stone scroll. Its quintessence cannot be fully perceived, yet its structure and principles remain clear—like the lingering grace of the beauties Mao Zhang and Xi Shi in their age.

    From the Tang, we have obtained two masters. Wu Daozi, skilled in painting, became renowned throughout the realm, standing alongside Han Yu's prose and Du Fu's poetry as one of the Three Excellences. We have two of his Buddhist paintings, and above them, Su Dongpo's own inscription and praise; also two painted monks. Wang Wei, perfected in landscape, achieved such celestial mastery that none can match it—surely because he brought the poet's vision to painting. We have one landscape scroll where water and mountains flow with pure nature, unmarred by human artifice.

    From the Song, we have obtained six masters. Guo Zhongsu excelled in painting pavilions and terraces—all rendered with ancient grace and singular beauty. We have his Snow-Cleared River Journey, where great vessels sail together, their figures and implements rendered with incomparable precision; also, with the imperial brush of Emperor Huizong, the High Pavilion Overlooking the River, where scholars and Daoists share a small boat beneath the eaves, one figure leaning at the rail in contemplation—such refined, dissolving grace that one forgets it is a painting.

    Li Gonglin, who styled himself the Recluse of Dragon Sleep, was widely learned and discerning. In his painting, intention precedes all else, and he excelled supremely in depicting figures. We have his scroll of Ning Qi Singing Long Notes. Emperor Huizong's imperial inscription declares: "The forms and spirit shimmer with refinement." Each time the scroll is unrolled, one hears the murmur of white stones beneath the southern mountains.

    Su Dongpo—we have a printed copy of his True Script Chaozhou Stele, and three bamboo paintings: Wind Bamboo, Snow Bamboo, and Spring Bamboo. Each displays refined vigor and ethereal grace, standing apart in the realm of painting.

    Wen Tong excelled in ink bamboo and shared the deepest friendship with Dongpo. We have one Wind Bamboo and four Bamboo Shoots scrolls. The great stalks stand upright with the majesty of ten-thousand-foot heights—surely these are what the ancients called the supple bamboo groves?

    Guo Xi: his landscapes and bare-branched forests stood unrivaled in his age. We have eight landscapes: one of spring showing a mountain lodge after revelry, a mounted figure at a river crossing; one of autumn showing a river village fisherman, rod in hand, sitting alone; one of north wind with drifting snow; one of summer with azure mist; one of water and stone; one of wind and rain; one of river and snow; one bearing a crane; two of ancient trees and distant plains; one landscape. All are majestic and strange, their brushstrokes alive and flying. We have also Geese Descending on Sandy Plain and River Heaven in Evening Snow, where frost-wind plays on chrysanthemums, one holds a zither gazing far; where cleared snow lies on the long river and a solitary boat casts its line—each suffused with leisured tranquility. We have one of a grove and pavilion, one of urgent rain, both on fans; two of fighting bulls with such force and vigor they seem to press and strain.

    Cui Que excelled in flowers and birds, earning acclaim in his time. We have one Autumn Flowers with Wild Ducks—wind and dew desolate, feathers and down scattered.

    From the Yuan, we have obtained twenty-one masters. Zhao Mengfu's calligraphy and painting were incomparably supreme. We have twenty-six samples of his running script and two ink bamboos. Xian Yu Shu, who studied calligraphy alongside Zhao Mengfu, we have six of his cursive scripts. Wang Gongyan excelled in flowers, grasses, birds, and beasts, taking only the idea to completion, yet possessing natural life-force. We have ten wood-flower paintings where all blooms burst forth and birds call to one another; also four flower-grass paintings and four fruit-tree paintings, where blossoms, fruits, and insects shimmer with manifest transformation. We have one of Withered Lotus with Heron, one of Yellow Hawk, three of Hunting Falcon, one of Peach Blossom with Hawk, one of Crow and Falcon—some with wings folded and body upright, some in flying assault—all seized with keen precision.

    Xie Yuan and Chen Yifu also excelled in birds and flowers. Xie Yuan has one Broken Crabapple Branch—refined simplicity, seeming the very work of nature. Chen Yifu has one Plum Blossom and one Apricot Blossom, their jade-like buds gleaming in sunlight, rare birds singing sweetly.

    Liu Baxi, Li Bi, Ma Yuan, Qiao Zhongyi, Liu Daoquan, Yan Hui, Zhang Yanfu, Gu Yingqing, Zhang Zihua, and Luo Zhichuan all earned renown in landscape. Liu Baxi's brushwork is bold and vigorous, excelling in strange cliffs and ancient trees. We have one River Pavilion After Snow, one Long Forest Filled with Snow, one Spring Dawn with Misty Haze, one Long River. Li Bi's brushwork is refined and minute, excelling in pavilions and figures. We have one Tengwang Pavilion, one Huaqing Palace, each of the Eight Scenes of Xiao and Xiang, twelve from the Twenty-Four Filial Pieties, one Ancient Tree, one Hanging Cliff with Lofty Pavilion. Ma Yuan's brushwork is elevated and graceful, incomparable. We have one of Long Pine and Thatched Hut, one of Stream Dwelling with Water-Jar. Qiao Zhongyi keeps both mountain-inch and wood-measure within rule and measure. We have eight colored landscapes. Liu Daoquan excels especially in gradations of tone. We have one ink-wash landscape. Yan Hui excelled in rocks and figures. We have one of Reading in the Mountains, one of Gathering Herbs in Secluded Grove, three Buddhist paintings. Zhang Yanfu has one Stream-Mountain After Rain, one Sheer Bank, one Long Forest Rolling Clouds, one Ink-Wash Cloud Mountain; also one Pine-Stone with poem by Ni Zan, and seven paintings with poems by Jie Xisi—verdant mountains, white clouds, shadowed depths, distant plains—all suffused with transcendent interest. Gu Yingqing has one of Blue Mountains and White Clouds—deep and secluded, of exalted refinement. Zhang Zihua has one of Sparse Forest Scattered Thinly and one landscape. Luo Zhichuan has one Snow Mountain, each reaching wondrous heights, their vital force pristine and clear.

    From our own realm, we have obtained one master: An Gyeon. His courtesy name was Gado, his childhood name Deuksoo. A native of Jikok, he now serves as Colonel of the Guard. By nature acute and penetrating, he has studied extensively among ancient paintings, grasping their essential principles, gathering the strengths of many masters and reconciling them all, skilled in every manner. Yet landscape is his supreme gift—seeking among the ancients, one rarely finds his equal. Having long accompanied the Hall of Constant Diligence, his paintings are the most abundant here. We have each of the Eight Scenes, one River-Heaven in Evening Radiance, one Sheer Bank with Twin Clarity, one Tumbling Torrent Flowing to Sea, one Where Heaven and River Are One Color, one Snow-Cleared Sky Cold, one Yellow Crane Tower, one Tengwang Pavilion, one After Rain Clear Skies, one Snow-Cleared with Lingering Cold, one Delicate Mist and Silk Ribbon, one Snow-Cleared Spread Like Silk, one Water Kingdom in Delicate Mist, one River Village Distant Green, one Grain Bursting Into Bloom, one Spring Clouds Emerging From Valley, one Secluded Clouds Over Reedy Ravine, one Wild Wind and Urgent Rain, one Twisted Dragon in Retreat, one Long Forest Narrow Path, one Milky Way Hanging Inverted, one Sheer Cliff, one Ink Plum and Bamboo, one Ink-Wash White Clouds, two landscapes, one Reed and Wild Geese, two Wood Flowers, one Long Pine. Additionally, among ancient paintings, there are eleven of uncertain attribution: one turtle, one pear blossom, one apricot blossom, one pine and crane, one flower and duck, one four oxen, one printed image of Wang Bo's deeds, one rear garden landscape, one hawk, one pavilion, one ancient tree landscape.

    In all, across five dynasties we have obtained thirty-five masters. Eighty-four paintings of landscape, seventy-six of birds, beasts, and flora, twenty-nine of pavilions and figures, and thirty-three examples of calligraphy—altogether two hundred and twenty-two scrolls. Alas, only one of devoted passion could accumulate such abundance.

    Though I have not myself mastered these arts, I have heard their principles expounded. Painting demands that one exhaust the transformations of heaven and earth, investigate the workings of yin and yang, grasp the essence of all things and the mutations of all affairs, allowing these to swell within the breast. Then, taking brush to silk, one concentrates spirit until thoughts align—desiring mountain, mountain appears; desiring water, water appears. Whatever one wishes to render must appear before the eye; then the brush moves in pursuit. Thus through the provisional forms in the heart one seizes the true reality—this is the painter's way. When understanding descends from the mind and responds through the hand, when mind and hand forget themselves and body merges with the object, becoming still and serene as if nature itself lay beyond the reach of pigment and brush—this transcends mere technique. One who observes such works, if he can cultivate his spirit through their serene refinement and nurture his vital force through their bold vigor, gains no small benefit. When he penetrates the principles of things and gathers broad knowledge and vast learning, he walks the same path as poetry. Yet who in this world has truly attained to such understanding?
  footnotes:
    - The Hall of Constant Diligence (匪懈堂) was likely the name of a private collection or studio belonging to the patron for whom this record was written.
    - Han Yu (韓昌黎), also known as Han Tuizhi, was a Tang Dynasty poet and essayist renowned for his prose. The reference alludes to the tradition of writing colophons and records for important artworks.
    - The 'Three Excellences' (三絶) traditionally referred to three supreme achievements in different arts. Here, Wu Daozi's painting is paired with Han Yu's prose and Du Fu's poetry as the highest examples of their respective arts.
    - Bai Juyi (白樂天), also known as Bai Letian, was a celebrated Tang Dynasty poet who wrote extensively about art and culture.
    - The Eight Scenes (八景) refer to a famous series of landscape subjects, particularly associated with the Xiao and Xiang rivers, which became a standard subject for painters.
    - An Gyeon (安堅) was a renowned Korean painter of the 15th century during the Joseon Dynasty, known for his landscape paintings that synthesized Chinese painting traditions with his own innovations.
    - The contrast between 'form and spirit' (形氣) and 'true reality' (眞狀) reflects classical Chinese aesthetic philosophy about how painting captures both literal appearance and essential nature.
